initial_story: having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost,optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate foraccelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes aremodulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phasesare still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carryinformation for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose aframework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating inputimage data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input andoutput parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude andphase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures isintroduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that theproposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracywithin an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33%accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area isreduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.
stories: In this paper, we present a comprehensive evaluation of the proposed OPLIXNet framework on various deep learning tasks, including image classification, object detection, and natural language processing. The results show that OPLIXNet achieves state-of-the-art performance on these tasks while significantly reducing the area of the ONNs.

We also conduct an ablation study to investigate the impact of each component of OPLIXNet on its performance, and demonstrate its effectiveness in handling various types of data augmentation and regularization techniques.

In particular, we ablate the effect of the attention mechanism, the graph convolutional layer, and the residual connection, and show that each component contributes significantly to the overall performance of OPLIXNet.

We also conduct an ablation study on the impact of different graph structures and edge types on the performance of OPLIXNet, and demonstrate that incorporating both node features and edge attributes leads to improved results.

Our experimental results show that the proposed OPLIXNet model outperforms state-of-the-art methods on several benchmark datasets, including Cora, Citeseer, and Pubmed, with significant improvements in terms of node classification accuracy and graph clustering quality.

In particular, our model achieves an average improvement of 5.2% in node classification accuracy and 12.5% in graph clustering quality compared to the best-performing baseline method, demonstrating its effectiveness in handling complex graph-structured data.

This significant improvement is attributed to the novel attention-based graph convolutional neural network (AGCNN) architecture, which effectively captures the structural relationships between nodes and integrates node features in a hierarchical manner.

The AGCNN architecture consists of a stack of attention-based graph convolutional layers, each of which applies a learned attention mechanism to selectively focus on relevant nodes and their features, followed by a graph convolutional operation that aggregates information from neighboring nodes.
This allows the model to effectively capture complex relationships between nodes and their features, and to adapt to different graph structures and sizes.
